{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:59:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15506"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598676"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15506"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15506"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.16,0.08,0.07,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8197"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74090"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5543"},{"type":"tags","id":"11555"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a skin check. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an office administrator but previously worked as a lifeguard for two years in her twenties. She has Fitzpatrick type II skin with multiple naevi. Her father died from melanoma at age 55. She reports spending most weekends outdoors at the beach. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has approximately 50 naevi distributed across her trunk and limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most strongly associated with her risk of developing melanoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cumulative occupational UV exposure","Current indoor occupation with weekend sun exposure","Duration of outdoor recreational activities","Previous outdoor occupation","Total number of lifetime sun hours"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of the complex relationship between sun exposure patterns and melanoma risk. While it might seem counterintuitive, the pattern of sun exposure is more important than the total amount of exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent indoor occupation with weekend sun exposure\u003C/strong\u003E represents intermittent intense sun exposure, which is more strongly associated with melanoma risk than chronic exposure. This pattern of exposure, where indoor workers receive occasional intense bursts of UV radiation, particularly on weekends or holidays, has been consistently shown to carry a higher risk than regular, more moderate exposure. A meta-analysis of 57 studies found a positive association between melanoma risk and intermittent sun exposure, but an inverse association for continuous over-exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious outdoor occupation\u003C/strong\u003E as a lifeguard, while significant, actually represents chronic sun exposure which has been shown to be associated with a lower risk of melanoma compared to intermittent exposure. Chronic exposure leads to protective skin adaptations including epidermal thickening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal number of lifetime sun hours\u003C/strong\u003E is less relevant than the pattern of exposure. Studies have shown that it\u0027s not the cumulative dose but rather the nature and timing of exposure that determines risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECumulative occupational UV exposure\u003C/strong\u003E has actually been associated with a reduced risk of melanoma in some studies, likely due to the protective adaptations that occur with regular exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuration of outdoor recreational activities\u003C/strong\u003E would only be relevant in the context of understanding the pattern of exposure rather than the total duration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors for this patient include her Fitzpatrick type II skin, multiple naevi, and family history of melanoma. However, the question specifically asks about exposure patterns. The paradoxical relationship between intermittent and chronic sun exposure and melanoma risk highlights the complexity of UV radiation carcinogenesis. Skin cancer risk is not just related to the amount of sun exposure, but also to the pattern, with melanoma risk particularly linked to habitual low sun exposure combined with high recreational sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intermittent intense sun exposure and sunburns in childhood are more strongly associated with melanoma risk than chronic sun exposure.","Indoor workers who receive occasional intense sun exposure are at higher risk of melanoma than outdoor workers with chronic exposure.","Personal risk factors for melanoma include fair skin, multiple naevi, and family history."],"references":["Long GV, Swetter SM, Menzies AM, et al. Cutaneous melanoma. Lancet 2023; 402;485-502. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(23)00821-8/abstract","Leiter U, Garbe C. Epidemiology of melanoma and nonmelanoma skin cancer--the role of sunlight. Adv Exp Med Biol. 2008:624:89-103. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18348450/","Skin Cancer Statistics and Issues Prevention Policy. Cancer Council. [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/about-us/policy-and-advocacy/prevention/uv-radiation/related-resources/risk-factors-epidemiology#sunRisk factors/epidemiology","Gandini S, Sera F, Cattaruzza MS, Pasquini P, Picconi O, Boyle P, et al. Meta-analysis of risk factors for cutaneous melanoma: II. Sun exposure. Eur J Cancer 2005 Jan;41(1):45-60 Available from: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15617990."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74090"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15506"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74090"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T14:13:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T14:14:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8197"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89931"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":n